data.survey.strategy: I was very confused how it was supposed to work, so I didn't have one
i tried to find a common thread that sounded correct
I compared clues and added them to my leads if they had relations to other leads
I was just trying to use logic to piece together the most common clues, and what commonalities they had.
i simply read the instructions
I just tried to find as many connections as I could and really look at the wording of each clue.

My strategy was to try and find details that related directly to how the watch was stolen first, which were the watch was in a case and was opened with a masonry drill, I assumed these to be true as they are concrete evidence not witness related.  From there I tried to find who had or was seen with a masonry drill, and then what vehicles were tied to said people.  Visual clues about the people seemed somewhat unreliable in figuring out who did it.

I first placed the most likely clues in the potential leads, and then carefully watched for my teammates to introduce clues which would either confirm my original intuitions, or force me to alter my clues to fit the narrative which seemed to be developing more concretely.
Sort clues based off the original promising leads in my notebook.
Focus on the person who seemed to have the most crossovers
I thought about what mattered like I Didn't think age mattered, but past convictions did.
I tried to focus on the person with the most leads.
I tried to look at clues that had similar information.
I followed the instruction given
My strategy is to go with evidence what was there at crime place and make decision
I read through the clues to see if any of them seem to match up. I especially looked at what they said was most likely the tool that was used to break in.
I feel like it was more of guessing to which ones made most sense.  I felt like I was missing information
I just tried to guess which made sense
I tried to pick the most logical clues with companion information.
I tried to put as many in the helpful clues as I could, and then narrow from there
I looked for a pattern and eliminated clues that did not fit the pattern
Put the clues together to build a picture.
I tried to start at the evidence and work my way out to the suspect
I evaluated the possible evidences.
Not sure, I just tried to find similarities in the clues and put them together like a storyboard I guess.
I based what was relevant on the four given clues.
Taking away the clues that are for sure false.
I read all of the clues and looked for ones that seemed to line up the most with the other clues.
I guess I tried to work backwards from clues that indicated someone who was near the watch, or where the watch was after it was stolen.
I WAS FOCUSED ON ALL THE POSSIBLE WAYS OF STEALING
I tried to focus on clues that were consistent and repeated and didn't just seem random, and that were focused around the watch.
I tried to check as many leads as possible and then filter only the most confirmed ones as relevant

Finding the items with the most potential evidence and trying to piece together a story.  I wish I knew if my choice was bald or wearing coveralls but I assume that information was in the hands of our weak link collaborator.
I looked at the clues and thought about which ones were more likely to be useful than the others.
Leaning on others for help.
I looked for the obvious details first.
I did my best not to select too many promising leads since that would result in losing money. I didn't chose any dead ends since they didn't matter.
I used to love strategy games but I have played any in a very long time and feel very rusty.
